  "text": "Potempa et al. [CITATION_1] are generally credited for the first randomized exercise trial involving hemiparetic stroke patients. The study compared 10 weeks of adapted bicycle ergometer exercise with a control intervention consisting of passive range of motion exercise. Results showed a significant between-group difference in VO 2 peak change over time, with the bicycle ergometer group (n ϭ 19) achieving 13% gains, compared with no change for controls (n ϭ 23). Though Fugl-Meyer sensorimotor scores were positively correlated with gains in peak VO 2 , neither of the treatment groups showed significant differences in functional outcome scores. This seminal study showed that aerobic exercise using cycle ergometry is feasible and improves fitness in chronic hemiparetic stroke, but provided no clear evidence that cycle exercise could improve neuromuscular function or functional mobility.",
